%==============================================================================
\chapter{Methodology}
\label{ch:methodology}
%==============================================================================

\section{Problem Framing and Model Purpose}

This thesis trains models to predict \textbf{Catastrophic Stock Implosions (CSI)} — permanent 
equity value destruction defined as an 80\% drawdown from peak followed by a zombie period of 
at least 18 months without recovery above $-20\%$ from the crash low. The prediction task is:

\begin{equation}
    \text{features}(t) \xrightarrow{\text{model}} \hat{y}(t+1)
\end{equation}

where $\hat{y}(t+1) = 1$ if firm $i$ enters a confirmed CSI event in year $t+1$. 
The one-year label shift is critical: features at year $t$ predict the \textit{following} 
year's outcome, preventing contemporaneous leakage from price features 
(e.g., \texttt{max\_dd\_12m}) into the CSI label triggered by the same crash.

\subsection{Two Investor Use Cases}

A central design decision is the distinction between two fundamentally different investor problems:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Ex-ante screening (M1):} At year $t$, \textit{before} any significant drawdown 
    is visible, screen firms based on fundamental accounting data alone. The model asks: 
    \textit{"Which firms should never enter the index?"} Features are limited to balance sheet, 
    income statement, and cash flow ratios — no price information. This supports the 
    \textbf{avoidance alpha} hypothesis: superior returns from systematically excluding 
    structural losers before crashes occur.

    \item \textbf{In-crisis triage (M3):} At year $t$, a firm is already in drawdown. 
    The model asks: \textit{"Will this become a permanent implosion or recover?"} 
    All features including drawdown severity (\texttt{max\_dd\_12m}) are available. 
    This achieves higher AP but relies on contemporaneous crash signals unsuitable 
    for ex-ante index construction.
\end{itemize}

The thesis prioritises M1 for index construction and uses M3 as a performance ceiling benchmark.

\section{Four-Model Architecture}

Four models are estimated to answer the two sub-questions of the thesis:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Model Architecture Overview}
\rowcolors{2}{gray!10}{white}
\begin{tabular}{clll}
\toprule
\textbf{Model} & \textbf{Feature Input} & \textbf{Classifier} & \textbf{Research Purpose} \\
\midrule
M1 & Fundamentals only ($\sim$452 features) & XGBoost + AutoGluon & Avoidance alpha; ex-ante screening \\
M2 & VAE(fund) $\rightarrow$ $z_{1..24}$ + recon error & XGBoost + AutoGluon & Sub-Q 1: does VAE add signal? \\
M3 & Full features ($\sim$471 features) & XGBoost + AutoGluon & Performance ceiling; triage benchmark \\
M4 & VAE(raw) $\rightarrow$ $z_{1..24}$ + recon error & XGBoost + AutoGluon & VAE compression of full features \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{M1 vs M2:} Answers Sub-Question 1 — does the VAE improve over raw fundamentals?
    \item \textbf{M1 vs M3:} Quantifies the \textit{price-stripping cost} — how much predictive 
    power is lost by removing price features for the purpose of ex-ante screening?
    \item \textbf{M3 vs M4:} Does VAE compression of the full feature set improve over raw features?
\end{itemize}

\section{Label Definition}

Following \citet{Tewari2024}, a CSI event for firm $i$ at time $t$ satisfies:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Crash trigger:} $\text{Drawdown}(t) < C = -0.80$ from the rolling 3-year peak
    \item \textbf{Zombie period:} Duration $T = 18$ months from crash low
    \item \textbf{Non-recovery:} Cumulative return from crash low stays $< M = -0.20$ 
    throughout the zombie window
\end{enumerate}

\noindent A firm is right-censored ($y = \text{NA}$) if the zombie confirmation window 
extends beyond the sample end date (December 2024). Multiple CSI events per firm are 
permitted, which deviates from \citet{Tewari2024} and allows the model to learn from 
serial-offender dynamics. A 27-combination sensitivity grid ($C \times M \times T$) 
is used for robustness analysis in Chapter~12.

\section{Temporal Validation Design}

Standard $k$-fold cross-validation is inappropriate for time-series data due to look-ahead 
bias. An \textbf{expanding window} design is used throughout:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Expanding Window CV Fold Structure}
\rowcolors{2}{gray!10}{white}
\begin{tabular}{cll}
\toprule
\textbf{Fold} & \textbf{Training Period} & \textbf{Validation Period} \\
\midrule
1 & \textit{Burn-in} (no training data) & 1993--1997 \\
2 & 1993--2001 & 2002--2006 \\
3 & 1993--2006 & 2007--2010 \\
4 & 1993--2010 & 2011--2015 \\
5 & 1993--2015 & 2016--2019 (= test set) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\noindent \textit{Note on Fold 1 (burn-in):} The panel starts in 1993, but no observations
exist prior to 1993 to serve as training data for Fold 1. The years 1993--1997 therefore
function as a \textbf{burn-in period} — they populate the initial training window for
Fold 2, ensuring that rolling 5-year features (e.g.\ \texttt{roll\_mean\_5y\_earn\_yld})
are populated with sufficient history before the first validation fold begins.
Fold 1 is skipped for CV metric computation; all subsequent folds use 1993 as their
training start date.

\noindent The three-way data split is:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Train} (1993--2015): hyperparameter optimisation via CV
    \item \textbf{Test} (2016--2019): model selection and threshold calibration
    \item \textbf{OOS} (2020--2024): final out-of-sample evaluation — never touched until evaluation
\end{itemize}

\section{Evaluation Metrics}

\subsection{Primary Metric: Average Precision (AP / AUCPR)}

Given class imbalance ($\approx 10\%$ CSI prevalence), AUC-ROC is misleading — a model 
achieving high ROC scores by correctly classifying the majority of non-CSI firms gains 
little practical value. \textbf{Average Precision} (area under the Precision-Recall curve) 
is the HPO objective and primary evaluation metric:

\begin{equation}
    \text{AP} = \sum_n (R_n - R_{n-1}) \cdot P_n
\end{equation}

Computed via \texttt{PRROC::pr.curve()} in R and \texttt{sklearn.metrics.average\_precision\_score} 
in Python to ensure consistency.

\subsection{Secondary Metric: Recall at Fixed FPR}

For index construction, the portfolio manager operates under a \textbf{false positive budget}: 
incorrectly excluding a high-growth "Ecstasy" stock (e.g., NVIDIA) is costly. 
\textbf{Recall at FPR $\leq 3\%$} is the primary economic metric:

\begin{equation}
    \text{R@FPR3} = \max \left\{ \text{TPR}(\tau) : \text{FPR}(\tau) \leq 0.03 \right\}
\end{equation}

This measures: given that at most 3\% of healthy firms are erroneously excluded, 
what fraction of true CSI events is captured?

\subsection{Threshold Calibration}

For the final index construction, threshold $\theta$ is calibrated on the test set 
to maximise F1-score (harmonic mean of precision and recall):

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Threshold Calibration — M3 XGBoost Test Set}
\rowcolors{2}{gray!10}{white}
\begin{tabular}{rrrrrr}
\toprule
\textbf{FPR} & \textbf{Threshold} & \textbf{Recall} & \textbf{Precision} & \textbf{F1} & \textbf{Firms flagged} \\
\midrule
1\% & 0.844 & 24.0\% & 77.0\% & 36.6\% & 417 \\
3\% & 0.789 & 47.3\% & 68.5\% & 55.9\% & 921 \\
\textbf{5\%} & \textbf{0.738} & \textbf{62.1\%} & \textbf{63.1\%} & \textbf{62.6\%} & \textbf{1,313} \\
10\% & 0.612 & 80.9\% & 52.7\% & 63.8\% & 2,049 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\noindent FPR $= 5\%$ is recommended for index construction (best F1 $= 0.626$).

%==============================================================================
\chapter{Data and Feature Engineering}
\label{ch:data}
%==============================================================================

\section{Data Sources}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{CRSP} (\texttt{crsp\_a\_stock.*}): Monthly equity prices, returns, 
    market capitalisation. Universe: NYSE, AMEX, NASDAQ common equities with 
    minimum 5-year listing lifetime. 19,647 unique \texttt{permno} identifiers.
    
    \item \textbf{Compustat} (\texttt{comp.funda}): Annual fundamentals. 
    Linked via CCM table (\texttt{crsp\_a\_ccm.*}) using LC/LU/LS link types 
    with P/C primary marker. 176,495 rows, 18,526 unique firms.
    
    \item \textbf{FRED API}: Macro variables — Federal Funds Rate, GDP growth, 
    unemployment, 10-year Treasury yield, HY spread, VIX, CPI inflation, 
    industrial production, recession indicator.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Look-Ahead Bias Mitigation}

A \textbf{3-month reporting lag} is applied: Compustat fundamentals dated at fiscal 
year-end $t$ are only joined to the annual panel for calendar year $t+1$ — 
reflecting the 10-K filing deadline of 90 days post fiscal year-end 
(\texttt{REPORTING\_LAG\_MONTHS = 3L}).

\section{Feature Families}

The full feature matrix contains $\approx 480$ engineered features across 11 families:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Feature Engineering Families}
\rowcolors{2}{gray!10}{white}
\begin{tabular}{clll}
\toprule
\textbf{Family} & \textbf{Description} & \textbf{Count} & \textbf{Key Features} \\
\midrule
1 & Point-in-time ratios & $\sim$40 & \texttt{earn\_yld}, \texttt{roa}, \texttt{leverage}, Altman Z \\
2 & YoY changes & $\sim$41 & \texttt{yoy\_*} \\
3 & Acceleration (2nd diff.) & $\sim$41 & \texttt{accel\_*} \\
4 & Expanding mean \& vol & $\sim$82 & \texttt{expmean\_*}, \texttt{expvol\_*} (lagged by 1) \\
5 & Peak deterioration & $\sim$18 & \texttt{peak\_drop\_*} (5-yr rolling peak) \\
6 & Consecutive declines & $\sim$10 & \texttt{consec\_decline\_*} \\
7 & Accounting momentum & $\sim$15 & \texttt{acct\_mom\_*} \\
8 & Rolling 3-yr stats & $\sim$90 & mean, min, max, SD, trend, autocorr \\
9 & Rolling 5-yr stats & $\sim$90 & same statistics over 5-yr window \\
10 & Price momentum \& vol & $\sim$8 & \texttt{mom\_1m/3m/6m/24m}, \texttt{vol\_12m/60m}, \texttt{max\_dd\_12m/60m} \\
11 & Macro interactions & $\sim$6 & \texttt{interact\_lev\_rate}, \texttt{interact\_ret\_vix}, etc. \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\section{Critical Design Decisions in Feature Engineering}

\subsection{Rolling Peak for Drawdown (Family 10)}

A key correction from a naive implementation: \texttt{max\_dd\_12m} and \texttt{max\_dd\_60m} 
use a \textbf{3-year rolling peak} rather than the all-time cumulative maximum. 

\noindent \textit{Rationale:} Using an all-time peak permanently depresses the drawdown 
reading for firms that experienced a distant historical high — a firm trading 
steadily at current levels appears to be in an artificially large drawdown relative 
to a decade-old peak. The rolling 3-year window measures \textit{current deterioration}, 
not historical distance from a potentially irrelevant all-time high.

\subsection{Multi-Year Price Feature Bug (Fixed)}

Previous versions computed \texttt{vol\_60m}, \texttt{mom\_24m}, and \texttt{max\_dd\_60m} 
inside a \texttt{by=.(permno, year)} group containing at most 12 monthly rows. This caused:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \texttt{vol\_60m} $\equiv$ \texttt{vol\_12m} (within-year SD only)
    \item \texttt{mom\_24m} always NA (24 months of data never available within one calendar year)
    \item \texttt{max\_dd\_60m} always NA (same reason)
\end{itemize}

\noindent \textbf{Fix:} Two-step approach. Within-year features (\texttt{mom\_1m/3m/6m}, 
\texttt{vol\_12m}, \texttt{max\_dd\_12m}) computed inside the annual group. 
Multi-year features (\texttt{mom\_24m}, \texttt{vol\_60m}, \texttt{max\_dd\_60m}) 
computed via an explicit firm-level loop accumulating cumulative price history up to each year-end.

\subsection{M1 Feature Set: Price Feature Stripping}

For the ex-ante screening model (M1), all price-derived features are removed from the 
feature matrix. This produces \texttt{features\_fund.rds} with $\approx 452$ features. 
Stripped features include:

\begin{itemize}
    \item All of Family 10: \texttt{mom\_*}, \texttt{vol\_*}, \texttt{max\_dd\_*}, 
    \texttt{ann\_return}, \texttt{log\_return}
    \item All derivatives of price features (YoY, acceleration, expanding stats, 
    rolling stats of \texttt{log\_return} and \texttt{ann\_return})
    \item \texttt{interact\_ret\_vix} (price $\times$ macro interaction)
\end{itemize}

\noindent \textit{Note:} \texttt{log\_mkvalt} is \textbf{retained} as a firm size proxy 
(market capitalisation), not a price direction signal. Its derivatives are also retained.

\subsection{Quantile Transform}

All feature matrices are transformed to uniform $[0,1]$ via QuantileTransformer 
\textbf{fitted on the training set only}, applied to test and OOS using the training ECDF. 
This prevents distribution shift between periods from affecting tree-based model 
split thresholds, and ensures neural networks within AutoGluon receive well-scaled inputs.

