\midrule
\textbf{WeightedEnsemble} & \textbf{0.6976} & Weights: LightGBMLarge=0.684, CatBoost=0.158, RF=0.105, LGBMXT=0.053 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Why LightGBMLarge Dominates}

LightGBMLarge achieves the highest single-model AP (0.697) and receives 68\% of the
ensemble weight in M1 and effectively 100\% in M3. Three hyperparameter choices explain this:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{num\_leaves=128 (vs default $\sim$31):} Financial distress follows
    highly non-linear, interaction-heavy patterns — e.g.\ high leverage is dangerous
    only when combined with low cash coverage and declining earnings. Deep trees with
    128 leaves can learn these multi-way interactions. Shallower models miss the
    compound deterioration dynamics that precede CSI events.

    \item \textbf{learning\_rate=0.03 with 4,687 rounds:} A slow learning rate with
    many iterations allows the model to make incremental, precise corrections rather
    than overshooting. The 4,687 rounds (vs 720 for standard LightGBM) indicate the
    model continued finding marginal signal across a long training trajectory —
    consistent with the high-dimensional, noisy nature of fundamental accounting data
    where each additional boosting step extracts a small but genuine signal.

    \item \textbf{feature\_fraction=0.9:} Using 90\% of features per tree introduces
    mild decorrelation between trees, reducing ensemble variance without the aggressive
    subsampling (50\%) used in the hand-tuned XGBoost. With 452--471 features, 90\%
    still provides full coverage of all feature families per split.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Why AutoGluon's XGBoost Underperforms}

AutoGluon's internal XGBoost scores 0.628 on the M3 holdout — the weakest
tree-based model — despite XGBoost being the strongest algorithm when hand-tuned
(0.682 test AP). The reason is entirely the default hyperparameter configuration:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{AutoGluon XGBoost vs Hand-Tuned XGBoost: Parameter Comparison}
\rowcolors{2}{gray!10}{white}
\begin{tabular}{lrrl}
\toprule
\textbf{Parameter} & \textbf{AutoGluon Default} & \textbf{Hand-Tuned (M3)} & \textbf{Effect of Default} \\
\midrule
learning\_rate      & 0.10  & 0.019 & $5\times$ too fast — overshoots optimal weights \\
subsample           & 1.00  & 0.50  & No row subsampling — higher variance \\
colsample\_bytree   & 1.00  & 0.50  & All features used per split — higher variance \\
gamma               & 0.00  & 4.40  & No split complexity penalty — memorises noise \\
lambda (L2)         & 1.00  & 5.00  & Insufficient leaf weight regularisation \\
alpha (L1)          & 0.00  & 2.70  & No sparsity — uses redundant features \\
n\_rounds           & 109   & 110   & Comparable (early stopping works correctly) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\noindent The Bayesian HPO explicitly searches for heavy regularisation
($\gamma=4.4$, $\lambda=5.0$, $\alpha=2.7$) and aggressive subsampling (50\%)
to counteract overfitting on the noisy high-dimensional feature space.
AutoGluon's default XGBoost configuration never explores this region,
confirming the value of explicit hyperparameter search for this problem.

\subsection{Why Neural Networks Underperform on Raw Features}

Both NeuralNetTorch and NeuralNetFastAI score near the bottom of the M1/M3
leaderboard (AP 0.529--0.653) but gain significant ensemble weight in the
latent settings (M4: 42\% weight for NeuralNetTorch). Three structural reasons
explain this pattern:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Early stopping fires aggressively:} NeuralNetTorch ran only
    3 epochs on the M3 holdout before early stopping. With 452--471 features
    and heavy class imbalance (10\% CSI prevalence), the network overfits
    within a handful of epochs and never reaches a well-generalised solution.
    The 4-layer, 128-unit architecture is not well-regularised for such
    high-dimensional tabular inputs.

    \item \textbf{Tabular financial data does not benefit from representation learning:}
    Financial ratios are already highly engineered — the model receives
    \texttt{roll\_mean\_5y\_earn\_yld} rather than raw financial statements.
    Neural networks excel at learning representations from raw, unstructured data.
    When features already encode domain-specific structure, the non-linear
    transformations of gradient boosting outperform neural architectures.

    \item \textbf{Improved performance on latent inputs (M4):}
    In the 25-dimensional latent space produced by the VAE, NeuralNetTorch
    scores competitively (0.555 holdout) and receives 42\% ensemble weight.
    The VAE has already performed the representation learning step — the compact,
    dense, continuous latent space suits neural architectures better than
    the raw sparse tabular matrix.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Why Random Forests Are Competitive but Not Dominant}

RandomForest and ExtraTrees score 0.651--0.680 on M3 — solid but consistently
below LightGBM variants. Their fixed hyperparameters (\texttt{n\_estimators=300},
\texttt{max\_depth=15}) are not tuned by AutoGluon, and two structural limitations apply:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Bagging without boosting:} Random Forests reduce variance through
    averaging but cannot correct systematic bias. Boosted models iteratively
    correct residuals — better suited to the difficult minority-class detection
    task where early trees will systematically underpredict CSI probability.

    \item \textbf{No explicit class-imbalance handling:}
    AutoGluon's RF/XT implementations do not apply \texttt{scale\_pos\_weight}
    or class-balanced sampling. With 90\% non-CSI prevalence, trees split
    predominantly on majority-class boundaries, reducing sensitivity on the CSI minority.
    The boosting algorithms handle this implicitly through residual weighting.
\end{itemize}


